# ================ THEORY =================

# Depth First Search (DFS) and Breadth First Search (BFS)
# are graph traversal algorithms used to visit all vertices
# of a graph systematically.

# A graph consists of:
# 1. Vertices (nodes)
# 2. Edges (connections)

# In this program:
# - An undirected graph is used.
# - The graph is represented using an adjacency matrix.
# - The user provides:
#     • Number of nodes
#     • Number of edges
#     • Connections between nodes

# Adjacency Matrix:
# A 2D matrix is used to represent graph connections.

# If graph[u][v] = 1:
# it means node u is connected to node v.

# Since the graph is undirected:
# graph[u][v] = 1
# graph[v][u] = 1

# Both directions are stored.

# Example:

# 0 — 1
# |
# 2

# Matrix Representation:

#    0 1 2
# 0 [0 1 1]
# 1 [1 0 0]
# 2 [1 0 0]


# ================ DFS THEORY =================

# DFS stands for Depth First Search.

# DFS explores a graph by going as deep as possible
# before backtracking.

# Working of DFS:
# 1. Start from a node
# 2. Mark it visited
# 3. Visit one connected unvisited node
# 4. Continue recursively
# 5. If no node remains, backtrack

# DFS uses:
# - Recursion
# - Stack internally

# In this program:
# visited[] array prevents revisiting nodes.

# DFS Traversal Example:

# Graph:

# 0 — 1
# |
# 2 — 3

# DFS starting from 0:

# 0 → 1 → back → 2 → 3

# Traversal Output:
# 0 1 2 3

# Advantages of DFS:
# 1. Simple recursive implementation
# 2. Uses less memory than BFS
# 3. Useful for path exploration

# Disadvantages of DFS:
# 1. Does not guarantee shortest path
# 2. Can go very deep
# 3. Recursive depth may increase


# ================ BFS THEORY =================

# BFS stands for Breadth First Search.

# BFS explores nodes level by level.

# Working of BFS:
# 1. Start from a node
# 2. Add node into queue
# 3. Remove first node from queue
# 4. Visit all connected unvisited nodes
# 5. Add those nodes into queue
# 6. Repeat until queue becomes empty

# BFS uses:
# - Queue
# - FIFO (First In First Out)

# In this program:
# queue list is used as queue.

# BFS Traversal Example:

# Graph:

#       0
#      / \
#     1   2
#    /
#   3

# BFS starting from 0:

# Level 1:
# 0

# Level 2:
# 1 2

# Level 3:
# 3

# Traversal Output:
# 0 1 2 3

# Advantages of BFS:
# 1. Finds shortest path in unweighted graph
# 2. Explores nearby nodes first
# 3. Good for level-wise traversal

# Disadvantages of BFS:
# 1. Uses more memory
# 2. Queue size may become large


# ================ ALGORITHM FOR DFS =================

# 1. Read number of nodes and edges
# 2. Create adjacency matrix
# 3. Store graph connections
# 4. Create visited array initialized with 0
# 5. Take starting node
# 6. Mark current node visited
# 7. Print current node
# 8. Check all adjacent nodes
# 9. If connected and unvisited:
#       recursively call DFS
# 10. Repeat until all reachable nodes are visited


# ================ ALGORITHM FOR BFS =================

# 1. Read number of nodes and edges
# 2. Create adjacency matrix
# 3. Store graph connections
# 4. Create visited array initialized with 0
# 5. Create empty queue
# 6. Take starting node
# 7. Mark start node visited
# 8. Insert start node into queue
# 9. While queue is not empty:
#       a) Remove front node
#       b) Print node
#       c) Check adjacent nodes
#       d) If connected and unvisited:
#             mark visited
#             insert into queue
# 10. Repeat until queue becomes empty


# ================ TIME COMPLEXITY =================

# DFS Time Complexity:
# O(V + E)

# BFS Time Complexity:
# O(V + E)

# Where:
# V = Number of Vertices
# E = Number of Edges


